{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17637079","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17637079"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:37:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:37:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17626"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17626","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17626"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0,0.53,0.37,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10340"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71810"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10340","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10340"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17626"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57299"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10035"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24189"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24198"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24246"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71810","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/71810"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe breakdown of dietary proteins requires coordinated enzyme activity throughout the digestive system.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary site of protein digestion?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Mouth","Oesophagus","Stomach","Small intestine","Large intestine"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Esmall intestine\u003C/strong\u003E is where most protein digestion takes place through the action of pancreatic proteases (trypsin, chymotrypsin, carboxypeptidases) that break down proteins into smaller peptides. Brush border enzymes then complete digestion to produce individual amino acids.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMouth\u003C/strong\u003E - Contains no proteolytic enzymes in saliva\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStomach\u003C/strong\u003E - Only initiates protein digestion via pepsin, accounting for a small portion of total breakdown\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOesophagus\u003C/strong\u003E - Functions only to transport food; no digestive enzymes are present\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELarge intestine\u003C/strong\u003E - Not involved in protein digestion as proteins are processed and absorbed earlier\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile protein digestion begins in the stomach, the small intestine is the major site due to its pancreatic enzymes and brush border peptidases that complete the process to produce absorbable amino acids.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Protein digestion requires multiple enzymes acting sequentially in different parts of the digestive system","Pancreatic proteases in the small intestine perform the majority of protein breakdown","Intestinal brush border enzymes complete the final steps of protein digestion to produce amino acids"],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019","Hall J. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier Health Sciences; 2021. https://clinicalkeymeded.elsevier.com/reader/books/9780323597128"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57299"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17626"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57299","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/57299"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-20T16:12:39+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-20T16:13:04+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10340"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71810"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4928","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4928"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udca9","name":"Gastrointestinal","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-31T09:50:24+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"13"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4942","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.